videos.title: 7 Things I HATE about Samsung Frame TV PRO (FULL Review)
videos.description: **Price it/Learn more here: https://amzn.to/475cn7k **   I've reviewed nearly every iteration of the Samsung Frame TV, since it was first released back in 2017, and I know a lot about it‚Ä¶ and since millions of you have seen those videos I decided it was time to buy this 2025 Pro version and test it out for myself so you can see if it might be worth it for you. Particularly because Samsung now has more competition in this art-TV category.  So what's new with the Samsung The Frame TV Pro, is it better than previous versions or is Samsung just jumping on the Pro Label bandwagon? What are the overall pros and cons and can I recommend it for you?  I bought the 65-inch Frame TV for my living room.  Join my channel for Exclusive members-only perks: https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCDGqNf14HSF9v8e-Qmp7VXA/join  ~Get My Newsletter: http://www.techgadgetscanada.com/newsletter-signup/  **May contain Affiliate Links: My YouTube channel is supported by the viewers. Occasionally I will include affiliate links in my reviews. This allows you to get more info easily, and I also may get a small commission from the click, which helps me keep the blog and this YouTube channel running. If you choose to use an affiliate link I thank you greatly for supporting my content. There's no obligation or cost to you for using these links. As an Amazon Associate I earn from qualifying purchases.   I‚Äôll quickly touch on the basics of a Frame TV for those who might be newer to the concept. In essence this is a TV that doesn't look like a TV; when it's not in use playing ultra high definition 4K video and TV shows, the screen shows highly realistic and super high resolution artworks. Thanks to a special coating on the screen, you're not simply getting a screensaver, you're actually getting a display that melts into the background and genuinely becomes part of your decor. Customizable wooden frames, and an included flush mount with no-gap lets you make the screen disappear into your space, or pop like real artwork.   What‚Äôs new? I'm going to quickly cover what the new features are with the Frame Pro version. For starters the one connect box is now wireless‚Ä¶ and I'll explain in more detail what that means, momentarily.   The display panel technology has also been updated; technically speaking the regular frame uses a QLED panel, while the pro version uses ‚Äò‚ÄôNeo QLED with Mini LED backlighting‚Äô‚Ä¶   Refresh rate on the pro version is also higher at 144hz (the regular Frame is 120hz) meaning it should be better able to handle faster action sequences and potentially even gaming. Samsung is also touting ‚Äòenhanced AI features‚Äô‚Ä¶ but I'll see what that actually translates to in practice. Samsung The Frame Pro is available in only 3 sizes: 65-inch, 75-inch, and 85-inch.   That's what's new with this version. Now let's get to what it's like to own one‚Ä¶  Set up & Installation If you're new to this TV the installation is not all that difficult. If you have an older model you might be disappointed to find that‚ÄîFrustration Number one‚Äî the bracket has been altered just enough to make it slightly incompatible with the new Pro version, so no re-using the old mounts. Previously known as the ‚Äòno gap wall mount‚Äô, you'll affix two mounting brackets onto your wall and a paper template included in the box makes this easier. Then attach to metal loops to the back of the TV. The loops will hang on the wall brackets to provide a stable yet flat support system for the TV that also offers a small amount of adjustability so you can get things square. Then you need to plug the TV in to power.  We had the TV installed and mounted in about an hour. Once the heavy lifting is done you'll plug in the new One Connect Box to power also, and get the TV onto your Wi-Fi network. From there you'll need to set up a handful of accounts and permissions and logins but you'll largely be ready to go.    ‚ÄòWireless‚Äô One Connect Box The most significant update in the Pro model is the new Wireless One Connect Box that comes with your Frame TV Pro. But this isn‚Äôt what it seems‚Ä¶ and don‚Äôt let what you can‚Äôt see here in my set up fool you‚Ä¶   With the Samsung Frame TV Pro here, Samsung will tell you it made a huge leap for all of us, by getting rid of the translucent wire completely with their new Wireless One Connect box. But the joke is on all of us because‚ÄîFrustration Number 2‚Äî while you don't have a thin translucent wire running from the One Connect box to the TV, you do still have to get power to the TV and for that Samsung has supplied a fat white power cable, and good luck hiding that without conduit inside the wall. Or‚Ä¶Here‚Äôs hoping you're one of those lucky few who has a power outlet high up on the wall where you can connect this to keep it out of view.

comments.comment_text_display: well he said "Micro RGB." He's not the one being deceitful, it's Samsung Electronics. "Micro RGB" is just a marketing term, whereas Micro LED is the industry accepted term for a self emissive panel consisting of LEDs. I agree though, super deceitful. "Micro" usually refers to 1/1,000,000 of a meter, also known as a Micron. In other words, I'm assuming the width of individual subpixels in a MicroLED display are within a size that scientists would consider "Micro Scale?" Actually, there are MicroLED panels with LEDs that are technically not Micro Scale. So yea, using the term "Micro," is pretty freaking misleading. I guarentee this display is an RGB backlit mini LED LCD. Vincent Teoh, of HDTVTest, recently tested the color gamut of Hisense's RGB mini led, and found it only covered 93% of BT2020. That is extremely impressive, but I heavily doubt this panel will be able to reach 100% of BT2020. Also, those measurements are done when the whole entire screen is a uniform color. The reason that QLED televisions only achieve around 80% bt2020 coverage is because the color filters aren't perfect, and since they are filtering their respective color from white light, and not all of the 'undesired" light gets filtered, each subpixel is "polluted," which hinders the display's color purity. This doesn't happen with RGB mini led because the backlight doesn't just consist of white light (mixture of blue LEDs with red and green quantum dot layer). If you want red to be displayed, the backlight just emits red. The problem is, when there are tons of different colors right next to each other, the backlight is going to have to send a mixture of those colors, and depend on the color filters to do the rest. An OLED display doesn't have this problem since each individual subpixel provides it's own light. So technically, for real world content, qd-oled  (and probably Tandem WOLED) still have higher color gamut.

comments.comment_text_display:
@crowntotheundergroud "for real world content, qd-oled (and probably Tandem WOLED)"

WOLED is pretty bad for color accuracy, because it's using dye/pigment based color filters rather than QDs.

The dye/pigment filters not only produce inaccurate color, but also waste a ton of the produced light (something like 2/3), which only makes LG's insane insistence on not using QD color conversion even worse.

With their greater OLED panels, QD color conversion and their long life OLED software they could dominate Samsung in the QD OLED space - it just doesn't make any sense to me at all.

The problem with RGB mini LED is that you basically end up sacrificing resolution of the local dimming array to get that color.

Because now instead of 1 white LED per region you need 1 for each RGB component.

Fine if you tripled the dimming array resolution first, but honestly I'd rather they just use that to increase the resolution of the array.

comments.comment_text_display:
Great review of the Samsung S95F, really appreciate the detailed breakdown! I was seriously considering this model when shopping for a new TV, but in the end I went with the LG OLED evo G5 in 83 inches instead.

A few reasons why I chose the G5:

I watch a lot of content in Dolby Vision, and since the S95F only supports HDR10(+), Dolby Vision support on the G5 was a big plus for me. The 83-inch size also made the decision easier, since LG‚Äôs panel in that size delivers excellent uniformity, brightness, and black levels for movie-watching in a darker room. On top of that, having HDMI 2.1 on all four ports and very low input lag was huge, as I game on both console and PC. The wide viewing angles and overall picture consistency just sealed the deal for my setup.

That said, the S95F is still an awesome TV, especially for bright rooms thanks to the anti-reflection treatment, and your review definitely helped me think through the strengths of each option. But for my personal use case, the G5 just checked more boxes.

Thanks again for the solid review!

Here in Hong Kong the OLED S95F in 77" is ~US$7,700, whereas the 75" Frame Pro is ~US$4,200 - so quite a big price difference - but a much better TV for those who want an 'Art TV'  to look good when not in use without compromising most of the other viewing features. comments.comment_text_display: Something reviews never consider is longevity from quality internal components. Samsung's superior quality to TCL, HiSense, etc., means those TVs will last years longer/thousands of hours longer. That's a big consideration for me. I had a Samsung that was outstanding for 15 years before giving it away, my sister had a Vizio that suffered black screen of death in 5 years. So if you think those up-and-coming brands represent better value-- unless you are cool with replacing sets every 10 years or less-- think again. Sure, the tech improves, it continually imlroves. But when you've been watching the same TV set for 10 years, you just don't care about that. (Now if we are talking OLED TVs then you have to cut that expectation for duration by a third compared to LED/QLED sets.)

comments.comment_text_display: my girlfriend bought a samsung and it had tons of horizontal lines across it in about 3 years.  I Have had my TCL for 2 years and it still looks perfect. I think people tend to buy Samsung for the name. Most of their lcd screens look not that great for the price and feature set imo. And as a brand they are NOT the same as they were 10+ years ago. The oled screens are nice though. I had a 2011 samsung that had amazing picture and it developed a flickering line 13 years later so I replaced it with another samsung.  And the picture was absolute trash and it had tons of DSE/ backlight bleed etc. Swapped it for a different model which had the same issues. Got the TCL after that and have been very happy with it.  Perfect uniformity. Very little DSE. Side note but My parents have had a Vizio since 2013 and picture is still perfect also. So it just depends I guess?

Okay, so what you're saying is this:
About 20 years ago when Mega-Electronic Companies, started phasing out the Cathode-Ray Tube TVs. Remember those big monitors. If you find one, put it's screen under a magnifying glass, simple one. Every strip is made of hundreds of sections laid out in a vertical line. So each of these sections is further divided into RGB(The Red Green Blue Dot) yes, that was the original RGB Dot.
After all this talk of going digital, the technique for constructing new technology remains the same as the one invented, what 70-75 years ago? We don't have anything new. If the technique is old, then I'll bet anything, that it's a old age pig with a modern lipstick, what I don't get is why they're charging 30,000 dollars for something that isn't even a newer concept. World had colored television since the 70s.
This concept of RGB Dot has been around since the time colour televisions were in existence.

comments.comment_text_display:
Some points that need to be noted:
1. Of the premium segments, Mini-LEDs offer higher brightness and color volume whereas OLEDs offer better viewing angles and contrast.
2. OLEDs tend to suffer a higher rate of Burn-In in hotter areas (more than 40 degrees), so if you are planning to buy a premium TV, and you are from such an area and your living room does not have AC, go for a Mini-LED TV instead of OLED.
3. If your budget do not allow for you to get a higher tier version of latest model, go for last year model of that tier, like if Samsung QN90F (2025) is out of budget, opt for QN90D (2024). Yes QN85F (2025) has some features that looks on paper better than QN90D, but 90 series is a higher tier than 85, as such will have more local-dimming zones and better HDR management (in some cases) and so on, which results in better experience. This cannot be followed when choosing mid-range TVs, as the upgrades year-on-year is greater in those segments.
4. Hisense Q series, TCL C series are extremely good deals which offer Samsung Mini-LED QLED and Sony Mini-LED levels of performance at lower price bracket. But their other ranges are things to be debated.
